%%TITLE
Comparison of HPV prevalence in HNSCC patients with regard to regional and socioeconomic factors.
%%ABSTRACT
HPV infection is considered as an independent risk factor for head and neck squamous cell carcinomas (HNSCC). Due to highly variable prevalence results in numerous studies, it is, however, difficult to estimate the relevance of HPV infection as risk factor for a specific patient collective. This study aimed to elucidate the disparities of HPV prevalence by analyzing socioeconomically and regionally different patient collectives. Two age, gender, stage and tumor location matched cohorts of 18 private health insured (PHIP) and 16 statutory health insured patients (SIP) suffering from an oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OSCC) and treated at a university hospital were screened for p16 overexpression and HPV infection by immunohistochemistry and PCR. In addition 85 HNSCC patients of an otolaryngology private practice (PPP) in a rural area were screened for p16 overexpression and positive cases were tested for HPV infection. HPV prevalence was 72.2% in the PHIP collective in comparison to 25.0% (p = 0.015) in the SIP collective with a significantly improved 5-year overall survival (p = 0.003) of the PHIP collective. The total HPV prevalence of PPP group was 7.1% with the highest infection rate in tonsillar carcinomas (33.3%) and a larger percentage of female patients in the HPV positive group (p = 0.037). This study shows that variable HPV infection rates in HNSCC can be caused by the selection of particular patient collectives, which suggest taking socioeconomic and regional factors into account for a decision on HPV testing, if it is not performed on a routine basis.
%%PATIENTS AND METHODS
Tumor material and patient data
A retrospective search of medical records of OSCC patients treated at the Department of Otolaryngology of the University Hospital Regensburg was performed to establish two age, gender, stage and tumor location matched cohorts of 18 private health insured patients (PHIP) and 16 statu- tory insured patients (SIP). Tumor material was derived from the following oropharyngeal locations: base of tongue and tonsils. For social histories a research of medical reports was performed. Alcohol abuse was defined as more than one alcoholic drink per day. A history of smoking within the last twenty years and/or a history of more than 10 pack years were applied for the definition of tobacco abuse.
In addition a database search of the Institute of Pathol- ogy, University of Regensburg, for HNSCC resection specimens and biopsies sent from one otolaryngology pri- vate practice was performed and generated a total of 88 patients from 1993 to 2010. The following anatomical sites
were included: Lips, oral cavity, tonsils, pharynx, nose, maxillary sinuses and larynx. Sufficient tissue material and usable data from HPV PCR and/or immunohistochemistry analysis were obtained for 85 patients. Three patients had to be excluded because DNA extraction could not yield sufficient material for HPV PCR. Drinking and smoking habits were traced back for 42 patients by phone interview. Overall survival dates could be obtained for 32 patients of the Department of Otolaryngology of the University Hos- pital Regensburg and 73 patients of the otolaryngology private practice from the cancer register of the Tumor Centre Regensburg. The study was approved by the Insti- tutional Review Board of the University Regensburg.
Immunohistochemistry and histologic evaluation
P16 was used as a surrogate marker. For immunostaining 4 lm thick sections of formalin-fixed, paraffin-embedded samples containing representative tumor material were deparaffinized and immunostained with CINtec R Histol- ogy V-Kit using the UltraView DAB Detection Kit on a Ventana BenchMark ULTRA autostainer (Ventana, Tus- con, AZ). P16 overexpression was assessed by evaluating the percentage of p16 expressing tumor cells. Strong cytoplasmatic staining was graded from 0 (0 % positive tumor cells) to 4 ([75 % of tumor cells positive). Tumor material with grade 4 was scored positive for p16 over- expression and analyzed for HPV infection. For tumor material graded 3 in p16 immunohistochemistry HPV PCR was performed as well. Immunohistochemical grading and nuclear grading as well as evaluation of tumor morphology was performed by an experienced pathologist.
Molecular analysis
The detection of HPV DNA was performed by Nested Multiplex PCR (NMPCR) as previously described by Sotlar et al. []. Briefly, 3–4 10 lm thick sections from paraffin-embedded tissue were used for DNA extraction. First the sections were deparaffinzed and stained with
0.01 % methylene blue for approximately 30 s. Microdis- section of the tumor tissue was carried out with a 22 gauge- needle under an inverted microscope (40-fold magnifica- tion). DNA extraction was performed using the commer- cially available High Pure PCR Template Preparation Kit according to the manufacturer’s instructions (Roche, Mannheim, Germany). For NMPCR 100 ng of extracted DNA was used. The NMPCR allows the detection of multiple HPV genotypes, including all high-risk genotypes (i. e. HPV 16, 18, 31, 33, 35, 39, 45, 51, 52, 56, 58, 59, 66, 68) and some low-risk genotypes (i. e. HPV 11, 42, 43, 44). In addition, coinfections with several subtypes can be analyzed by this method. The assay consists of a PCR
cocktail with an outer pair of E6/E7 consensus primers and several inner type-specific primers. PCR products were analyzed by agarose gel electrophoresis. A PCR assay for a fragment of the human b-globin housekeeping gene served as positive control and guaranteed the integrity of the analyzed DNA.
Statistical analysis
Fisher’s exact test was used for assessing statistically sig- nificant differences between patient and tumor character- istics of HPV positive and negative patients as well as private and statutory health insured patients. Unpaired two- tailed t test was applied for age discrimination among HPV positive and negative patients. Statistical significances of 5-year overall survivals were calculated by log rank test for univariate analysis and by cox regression for multivariate analysis. P values less than 0.05 were considered statisti- cally significant.
